Enforced Economics: Individual Fishery Quota Programs and the Privileging of Economic Science in the Gulf of Mexico Grouper-Tilefish Fishery David Griffith

Individual Fishery Quota (IFQ) programs allocate shares of an established quota of specific species of fish to individual fishermen  based on their history of participation in the fishery, effectively privatizing the fishery even though government agencies maintain  the right to alter the shares, species covered, or other attributes of the program. Fishery managers typically use economic arguments  about efficiency, planning, and avoiding tragedies of the commons, along with safety issues, to justify IFQ programs, suggesting they  professionalize fisheries. Embedded in these arguments is the implication that fishermen have not been using their human, fixed, or other  forms of capital efficiently, and that they need to begin thinking more like businessmen—that is, more like neoclassical economists  would like them to think. Based on research on the Gulf of Mexico Grouper-Tilefish IFQ program, this article argues that IFQ programs,  while encouraging fishermen to behave more like businessmen, do not reflect historical participation in the fisheries of the Gulf. Key words: critique of economics, privatization, capital concentration, Gulf of Mexico fisheries, IFQs The academic field of economics rose with our  economy,  and  everyone,  not  just  economists,  talked of costs and earnings and cash equiva- lents and quantitative easing. Then the economy  collapsed, and all we had left was this shitty  vocabulary. —Amy Rowland, The Southern Review (2017:159) Prize in economics to the political scientist Elinor Ostrom  rather than the entire prize to economists (Elliott 2009). De- spite repeated economic crises through the 20th and into the  21st centuries—including bank failures in the United States,  United Kingdom, Finland, Sweden, Israel, India, and Iceland;  stock market crashes; energy crises; and debt crises—many  neoclassical economists continue to remain steadfast to as- sumptions about human behavior and methods of analysis that  drive policy and influence the implementation of programs  designed to encourage people to behave the way economists  would  like  to  think  they  behave. While  some  economists,  particularly  behavioral  economists,  have  questioned  the  orthodox assumptions of their discipline, most economists  in  fisheries  management  positions  still  subscribe  to  ideas  about human decisions deriving from individual desires to  maximize profits.

Along with other social sciences, anthropology has had  a  long,  contentious  relationship  with  economics,  much  of  which comes from economic science evolving in close as- sociation with the development and expansion of capitalism  (Granovetter  1985;  Polanyi  1971;  Scott  1976;  Thompson  1971). In the case of anthropology, this dates back to such  classics as Mauss’s The Gift (1925) and Karl Polanyi’s Primi- tive, Archaic, and Modern Economies (1971), but critiques  of economic science have also come from more recent works  like Eric Wolf’s (1982) on the slave and fur trades and other  commodities, Sidney Mintz’s (1985) pioneering social his- tory  of  sugar, Annette  Wiener’s  (1992)  understandings  of

inalienable wealth, and William Roseberry’s (1989) essays in  political economy. The relationship reached its most heated  historical moment during the formalist-substantivist debate of  the 1960s, when formalists attempted to apply the principles  of  neoclassical economics to  non-Western  institutions like  Tiv  bride  wealth  (Bohannan  1955;  LeClair  and  Schneider  1968). By contrast, substantivists argued that such principles,  as products of Western capitalism, were irrelevant at best and  misleading at worst, demonstrating how difficult it was to  understand practices like redistribution, gift exchange, and the  use of special purpose money through a neoclassical econom- ics lens (Dalton 1961). Much of the debate revolved around  the issue of “maximization,” or the assumption that people  made  economic  and  other  kinds  of  decisions  to  maximize  benefits to themselves. This assumption is central to Hardin’s  (1968) tragedy of the commons, which has influenced a good  deal of fisheries policy, whereby individuals maximizing their  personal  benefits  (e.g.,  catching  as  many  fish  as  possible)  lead to high costs to society (e.g., depletion of fish stocks).  Although the formalist-substantivist debate was never  resolved,  legacies  of  the  debate’s  influence  remain.  Some  anthropologists embraced, for example, modernization theory  or economic decision making (e.g., Maiolo and Orbach 1982),  which draw heavily on neoclassical economics, while others  migrated toward political economy, which places class and  social relations at the center of economic behavior (Durren- berger 2008; Griffith 1987; Roseberry 1989). Still others have  developed the field of moral economy, which demonstrates  that moral considerations and sentiments—particularly the  right to subsistence and economic livelihoods—can not only  drive economic decisions but also can organize entire local  economies (Griffith 2009; Scott 1976; Thompson 1971). Es- pecially relevant here, Pinkerton (2015) considers the moral  economic principles at work in British Columbia’s small-scale  salmon and halibut fisheries, where she interprets common  systems of sharing

conomies (Griffith 2009; Scott 1976; Thompson 1971). Es- pecially relevant here, Pinkerton (2015) considers the moral  economic principles at work in British Columbia’s small-scale  salmon and halibut fisheries, where she interprets common  systems of sharing in fisheries (of the catch among the crew  and of the entire resource among different vessels and fleets)  as deriving from a moral economic sentiment of fairness.

In fisheries management circles, the influence of econo- mists has not quite paralleled that of biologists, whose influ- ence  has  long  been  privileged  in  developing  regulations;  nevertheless, fisheries economists have attempted to model  fishing  behavior  based  on  a  number  of  assumptions  about  factors  that  drive  human  motivation  and  decision  making.  Most  of  these  factors  are  related  to  market  dynamics  and  profit motives, assuming that fishing enterprises are driven  by market considerations because the costs of not paying at- tention to the market are outcomes such as business failure,  bankruptcy, and loss of one’s ability to continue fishing. Yet,  most anthropologists who have studied commercial fisheries,  in the United States and abroad, have rejected the notion that  commercial fishing families and fishing vessels conform to  capitalist principles, instead understanding them as family- based livelihoods that incorporate into their economic deci- sions and behaviors factors such as kinship, job satisfaction,  well-being, and one’s relationship to natural resources and  local environments as much as income, expenses, markets,  and  profits  (Acheson  1987;  Durrenberger  1997;  Garcia- Quijano  et  al.  2015;  Griffith,  Garcia-Quijano,  and Valdes- Pizzini 2013; Pinkerton and Davis 2015; Valdes-Pizzini and  Garcia-Quijano 2009).

Ironically, these observations were initially developed by  economists (working with anthropologists) in New England,  where the groundfish fisheries are large and industrialized,  yet  in  many  cases,  “kinship  based”  rather  than  capitalist  (Doeringer, Moss, and Terkla 1986). These initial observa- tions were enhanced by anthropologists who entered fisher- ies anthropology from peasant studies (Durrenberger 1995,  1997), political economy (Durrenberger 2008; Griffith 1999;  Griffith and Valdes-Pizzini 2002), and cognitive anthropology  (Garcia-Quijano et al. 2015). These studies, moreover, have  been conducted in fisheries around the world (e.g., Griffith  2011;  Jentoft  and  Kristofferson  1989;  McCormack  2010;  Pinkerton and Davis 2015). Anthropological studies of fisheries typically place fish- ing families in larger social, cultural, economic, and political  contexts, understanding the behavior of commercial fishing  as embedded or entangled in multiple social and economic  processes that have altered coastal environments around the  world. A short list of these would include seafood imports  from aquaculture operations in regions with low land, labor,  and regulatory costs; gentrification; user and gear conflicts;  struggles  over  cultural  heritage;  the  value  of  traditional  ecological knowledge in crafting fisheries regulations; and  environmental controversies involving porpoises, turtles, and  other iconic marine species.

Despite continued ethnographic work questioning profit  motives  in  commercial  fishing  operations,  many  neoclas- sical  economists  continue  to  represent  fishing  operations  as economic firms that, if failing to make a profit, are eco- nomically inefficient. While not all economists contribute to  this  perspective,  most  fisheries  economists  responsible  for  designing Individual Fishery Quota (IFQ) Programs do fall  into this camp. Indeed, IFQs have been developed to specifi- cally address economic inefficiency in fisheries that fisheries  biologists designate as overfished or experiencing overfishing.  Briefly, IFQ programs allocate shares of an annual quota of  a fish species to individual commercial fishermen who have  been  able  to  demonstrate  a  history  of  participation  in  the  fishery over a designated time period prior to the implementa- tion of the IFQ. Individuals thus “own” a percentage of the  fishery resource. Every year, this translates into numbers of  pounds they can catch per year based on the annual quota,  which are set by governing bodies (regional fishery manage- ment councils and NOAA fisheries). In most IFQ programs,  holders of shares have the option of fishing their allocation  themselves, leasing some or all of their annual allocation to  other fishermen, or selling their shares. Although this appears  to privatize the fishery, it is not complete privatization because  the state reserves the right to reallocate shares, change the  percentages of the shares allocated, close the fishery, reduce  the quota to a point that it is worthless, and intervene in an  individual’s access to the fishery in other ways. This contin- ued state presence in fisheries is believed to keep corporate  interests such as Wal-Mart or Red Lobster or environmental  groups like the Nature Conservancy from buying all of the  shares and either monopolizing the fishery or protecting the  fishery. State oversight and management of the program is  paid for by an administrative fee of 3 percent on all fish landed  under the program.

IFQ programs address the problems of perceived and real  overfishing with at least two standard economic solutions:  reducing  overcapacity  (too  many  vessels  chasing  too  few  fish) and improving economic efficiency. Sculptors of IFQs  also wish to address a third, safety issue called derby fish- ing, or racing to fish as soon as the season opens to catch as  much of the annual quota of a species as possible, regardless  of weather conditions or possible mechanical problems with  vessels. It could be argued that reducing derby fishing is also  an economic efficiency issue, allowing for increased planning,  preventing the dumping of too many fish on the market at one  time and lowering ex-vessel prices, and reducing the risks  of days lost and costs of occupational injuries and deaths.  Finally, IFQs tend to be based on the logic of the tragedy of  the commons, or the idea that open-access resources are more  subject to over-exploitation than privatized resources, in that  people externalize to society the costs of over-exploitation  while reaping immediate individual benefits.

Although  designed  for  fisheries  that  are  overfished  or  are  experiencing  overfishing,  IFQs  are  by  no  means  the  only management tool available to address one or both of  these phenomena.1 Others include limited entry, seasonal, or  long-term closures of the fishery; gear restrictions; licensing  and permitting regulations; and the establishment of marine  protected  areas  (MPAs)  or  sanctuaries;  in  most  cases,  one  or more of these management strategies has been used prior  to the implementation of an IFQ (Acheson, Apollonio, and  Wilson 2015; Copes 1986; Gibbs 2010; McCay et al. 1995).  Most of these management tools have the goal of protecting  fish  stocks,  which  has  been  the  highest  priority  since  the  2007 reauthorization of the Magnuson-Stevens Fishery Act.  National Standard 8 of the Act also specifies that management  tools need to consider consequences of regulations on fishing  communities, but only after fish stocks have been protected.  As the name implies, IFQs protect fish stocks by deter- mining an annual quota that is deemed sufficiently low to  allow fish populations to reproduce; these quotas have been  called by a number of names and acronyms (e.g., Total Allow- able Catch or TAC; Annual Catch Limit or ACL; Allowable  Biological Catch or ABC); in the Gulf of Mexico, this quota  is set by the Gulf of Mexico Fishery Management Council  on recommendations from their staff and their Scientific and  Statistical Committee (SSC).2 The SSC considers multiple  biological studies to determine whether or not their findings  constitute the best available science and then makes recom- mendations to the Council about things like the annual quota  for the grouper-tilefish fishery. Most of the biological data  have been compiled by career biologists on the Council; the  Council  staff  also  includes  economists,  an  anthropologist,  and other scientists, and reviews independent studies as well  as conducts its own research. While the quotas are set by the  Council, NOAA fisheries is the regulatory body that imple- ments and enforces the quota along with the other dimensions  of the IFQ program.

In  the  Gulf  of  Mexico,  two  IFQ  programs  have  been  introduced in the past decade: one for red snapper (Lutjanus  campechanus)  in  2007  and  a  second  for  a  grouper-tilefish  complex in 2010. The grouper-tilefish IFQ included thirteen  deep water species: gag grouper (Mycteroperca microlepis),  red grouper (Epinephelus morio), snowy grouper (Epineph- elus niveatus), speckled hind (Epinephelus drummondhayi),  warsaw grouper (Hyporthodus nigritis), yellowedge grouper  (Hyporthodus flavolimbatus), black grouper (Mycteroperca  bonaci),  scamp  (Mycteroperca  phenax),  yellowfin  grouper  (Mycteroperca  venenosa),  yellow  mouth  grouper  (Mycte- roperca interstitialis), blueline tilefish (Caulolatilus microps),  golden tilefish (Lopholatilus chamaelonticeps), and goldface  tilefish (Caulolatilus chrysops). IFQ programs are reviewed  by  the  Gulf  of  Mexico  Fishery  Management  Council  an- nually, with a comprehensive review completed every five  years. This article draws on research for the five-year review  for the grouper-tilefish IFQ program, although the two IFQ  programs overlap in that many Gulf of Mexico commercial  fishermen participate in both programs.

Research for this article was conducted in four regions  of the Gulf of Mexico from the fall of 2014 to the summer  of 2016: Southwest Florida, near the Tampa-St. Petersburg  area; the Florida Panhandle; the Bayou La Forche Corridor  of Louisiana; and four ports in and around Galveston, Texas  (see Figure 1).3 Research in each region was conducted by an  individual anthropologist, but the team worked together on  research design issues and the preparation of the final report.  I was responsible for research in the Florida Panhandle, and  most of the data for this article come from that region; how- ever, I have drawn on the other three reports as well. The research was primarily qualitative, with windshield  surveys of the regions and observations followed up by in- terviewing with the use of an interview guide. Sampling was  accomplished with lists of grouper-tilefish shareholders and  authorized grouper-tilefish dealers provided by the National  Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration’s Southeast  Regional  office  in  St.  Petersburg,  Florida,  referrals,  and  intercepting captains and crew at commercial marinas and  other locations. Research assistants working with me phoned  stakeholders at random prior to my fieldwork in the Florida  Panhandle, asking them if they were willing to be interviewed  about the IFQ program; very likely due to the contentious  nature of the program, of those contacted, only those who  no longer fished their allocation refused to be interviewed.  Most participants wanted to add a voice to the study. I was  able to complete and digitally record seventy-two interviews  Figure 1.  Map Showing Study Communities with individuals representing different segments of the com- mercial fishing industry and related fields (e.g., marine exten- sion agents, port agents, harbor masters); the total number  of interviews for the entire project was 176, accounting for  more than 25 percent of the estimated 700 or so IFQ holders.  One hundred forty-two of the interviews were concentrated  in Florida, as the grouper-tilefish fishery is more important  there than in either Louisiana or Texas (Griffith et al. 2016).

While  tilefish  is  less  well-known  than  grouper,  deep  water species like grouper and snapper have long been highly  valued as seafood in the Gulf as well as across the United  States. They tend to be harvested by hook and line, with long  lines and bandit reels the most common gears utilized. Long  lines are, as the name implies, lines several hundred meters  long  with  multiple  hooks;  bandit  reels  are  hook-and-line  electric reels mounted on the sides of vessels, with one crew  person usually operating two to three reels. Fishing trips can  take only a day or two or can last for up to a week to ten days,  depending on the vessel’s storage capacity, distance to fishing  grounds, and other considerations.  Grouper-tilefish  vessels  can  range  in  size  from  around  thirty to sixty feet, usually operating with a captain and a crew  of one to three mates, and some vessels that participate in the  IFQ program operate as charter boats during the summer (tak- ing tourists out to fish) and fish commercially during the winter.  Neither the fleet nor the grouper-tilefish “community,” in so  far as there can be said to be one, is concentrated in any one  location, but dispersed over the Gulf in a variety of large and  small, public and private marinas, many of which also double  as landing and seafood handling or processing centers, where  licensed IFQ dealers handle the grouper-tilefish catch. Outside  Gulf of Mexico’s Grouper-Tilefish Fishery of a few fishing associations representing, for example, IFQ  shareholders or charter boat captains, it is doubtful whether or  not a geographically distinct fishing community exists in the  Gulf of Mexico; although, several ports (e.g., Bayou La Batre,  Alabama; Cortez, Florida) do have multiple fishing operations  and supporting infrastructure. In most of the ports included  in our study, commercial fishermen were able to access dock  space,  fuel,  ice,  repair  services,  financial  services,  seafood  dealers and processors, and other support infrastructure.

Historically, grouper-tilefish captains and crew do not  specialize  in  one  or  two  deep  water  species,  and  instead  range over much of the marketable finfish resource, a strategy  common to fisheries in many parts of the world (McCormack  2010; Valdes-Pizzini and Garcia-Quijano 2009). During our  interviews, fishermen reported targeting both additional deep  water species like Vermillion snapper, as well as pelagics like  king  mackerel,  amberjack,  dolphin  fish  (Mahi  Mahi),  and  wahoo. Grouper-tilefish crews, however, tend not to target  the Gulf’s most valuable species, shrimp, or the high-value  spiny lobster of the Florida Keys, although these two shell- fish—along with stone crab, blue crab, and other shellfish  species—are also important commercial species in the Gulf.  As noted earlier, the distribution of shares in the grouper- tilefish fishery was based on historical participation in the fish- ery. Those who could show landings data during the five-year  period chosen by fisheries regulators, 2001-2006, received  shares of the annual quota, which annually translate into a per- centage of the number of pounds allowed that year. Because  historical participation in the fishery varied, and because some  people had problems during the 2001-2006 period, the initial  distribution of the shares was highly uneven, with some people  now allowed to catch many thousands of pounds annually and  others allowed to catch as few as under ten.

Still, the initial distribution of shares accomplished two  goals  viewed  as  positive  by  economists:  first,  it  converted  mere  resource  users  into  resource  owners,  creating  a  form  of property similar to private property for those who owned  capital  in  the  form  of  vessels  and  reef  permits;4  second,  it  rewarded those who had specialized in the grouper-tilefish fish- ery rather than those who fished over the whole resource. As  one might predict, individuals who received few to no shares  hotly contested both of these outcomes, although their reasons  for  opposition  varied  along  a  few  lines.  By  contrast,  those  who received substantial shares tended to express opinions  supporting the arguments of neoclassical economic science.  Several fishermen who benefited from the program, for  example, argued that the allocation reflected fishing ability  or historical dedication to the fishery, implying or explicitly  stating that fishermen who did not receive shares very likely  were among the fishery’s least talented members. According  to one such fisherman:  Another fisherman invoked the argument of privatization: By contrast, many observers of the IFQ program viewed it  as  inherently  unfair.  One  who  actually  benefited  from  the  program  put  it  this  way:  “It  [the  grouper-tilefish  IFQ  pro- gram] cut out a lot of people. It hurt people who didn’t have  the history. I had people working for me who didn’t get any  because the boat owner got the quota. Captains and crew who  had been working their whole lives got no quota because it  went to the boat owner, so they had nothing to show for their  life’s  work.”  Similar  sentiments  were  expressed  by  those  who received allocation yet not enough to make much of a  difference in their annual fishing income. “I can go out and  work hard for four days and I’m done,” one said. “I can’t  keep up the boat all year to fish for four days. It gives me  something—a commodity—but it ties my hands. Realistically,  you can catch all those shares in two trips—two weeks out  of the year and I’m done.”

A lot of people who didn’t get much, they weren’t very  good  from  the  beginning.  They  weren’t  serious  fisher- man. Some were good fishermen, but they got antsy with  the regulations coming and sold out. One guy across the  bayou sold out for pennies when he would have been set  for life, and now he blames the IFQ program for putting  him out of business. Now, with the IFQ, his boats aren’t  worth  anything,  but  with  the  IFQ  they  are.  My  boats,  now, are paid off. I voted for it. I knew it would cut into poundage a bit, but  you owned it. It wasn’t just “fish ‘til you die, fish ‘til you  can’t fish, sell your boat and your book of numbers and  go away.” You had something at the end. You can horse  trade, lease them, all that. I got a good lick, good catch  record,  came  out  to  about  half  of  what  you  fished  in  a  year, but the increase in value of fish and value of shares  made up for that. A more serious claim came from fishermen who either  implied or stated outright that the initial distribution of shares  was  a  corrupt  process,  with  only  those  close  to  the  Gulf  Council or fishery managers receiving adequate allocation.  “The government gave that quota to the fishermen. They got  to vote on it, yeah, but the only ones that got to vote were  the ones that ‘substantially fished’ those species. It was the  ones that were going to get the most of the quota, they were  the ones who got to vote.”

Along the same lines, another fisherman characterized  the IFQ program as a failure, saying that it was designed by  special interests who kept increasing the amount of poundage  you needed to have a vote in whether or not to implement  an IFQ so that they would be assured a positive outcome.  He had even written down his objections to the program on  a yellow legal pad just in case the need arose for a written  document. It read: “IFQ Failure. This system was designed by  persons of special interests—theirs. From the very conception,  the number of quota and pounds were elevated upwards to  eliminate sheer numbers of fishermen that would be able to  vote.”  He went on to claim that he was involved in the fishery  from the beginning, but he didn’t get a vote, adding, “They  kept raising the number of pounds to have a select few in  the club. When they were planning the program, early on  the council people—particularly the long-liners, who were  not going to vote against it—realized that they were going  to have too many people voting and that there was a chance  a  lot  of  those  would  vote  against  it.  So  they  kept  raising  the limit.” Others questioned the fundamental moral basis of the  allocation, claiming that the state had no right to divide up a  resource that belongs to the people. One combination charter  boat  fisherman  and  commercial  fisherman,  who  received  enough shares for just two trips per year, said: This fisherman alluded to one of the key impacts of the pro- gram: establishing a class of IFQ shareholders that non-IFQ  shareholding fishermen need to go through to gain access to  the grouper-tilefish fishery. This is, of course, similar to the  wage labor relationship—the central social relation of pro- duction within capitalism—yet different in that fishermen are  not paid a wage but a share of the catch. Under wage labor  relationships, workers gain access to the means of production  (e.g., natural resources and tools) only to produce a product  for the owners of those means of production, for which they  are paid an agreed-upon wage. Typically, before and after the  IFQ, shares of the catch go to the captain and crew, the boat

It’s a natural resource. Young people can’t get into this  business  because,  number  one,  fuel  is  $3.00  a  gallon,  equipment is expensive, and then, on top of this, you have  to lease shares from these IFQ guys. The only people who  are going to end up fishing are going to be like sharecrop- pers of the old days…. I don’t feel like it should belong  to just a few people. It’s like deer or turkeys or any other  natural resource. It shouldn’t be just a few people. owner, and the vessel, with each receiving a third. What has  changed under the IFQ is that, in all cases, the vessel owners  collect the 3 percent recovery fee from the captain (if not the  boat owner) and crew and, in some cases, vessel owners lease  their allocation to captains and crew prior to catching any fish.  When captains and crew have to lease the allocation, both the  recovery fee and the cost of leasing the fish come from their  share. Pinkerton and Edwards (2009) argue that leasing fees  have  actually  decreased  efficiency  in  IFQ  fisheries,  stifled  innovation, and exacerbated differences in market power and  wealth in IFQ fisheries.  Under  the  most  exploitative  sharecropping  arrange- ments, landowners provided the land and extended credit to  sharecroppers, who then used their own and family labor and  provided tools, fertilizers, seeds, etc. to raise a marketable  crop (Kayatekin 2001; Mandle 1983). At harvest, the crop  was divided (usually unevenly) between the landowner and  the  sharecropper,  and  the  sharecropper  repaid  some  or  all  of  his  or  her  debt.  Commonly  in  the  United  States  South,  sharecroppers’ shares were not enough to cover their debt,  and they remained in debt (and effectively enslaved) to the  landowner  until  the  following  harvest  (Daniel  1992).  One  fisherman summarized a similar situation remarkably well  when he said:

These developments constitute a significant change in labor  relations in the industry, with potentially long-term detrimen- tal consequences to the reproduction of the fleet. Fishermen  wanting to enter the grouper-tilefish fishery now must bear the  additional cost of leasing allocation and paying the recovery  fee or buy shares in the fishery from current shareholders. At  the same time, current shareholders need not fish at all, or  can fish for other species, and earn income from the fishery  by simply leasing their shares to others. Despite these consequences, seen by many fishermen  as negative, these developments suggest that the IFQ pro- gram has accomplished one of its intended goals: reducing  overcapacity.  Because  the  IFQ  program  has  effectively  closed the fishery to those who cannot afford to lease al- location, those fishermen must now fish for the owners who  received allocation, move to other fisheries, or leave Gulf  fisheries altogether. Each of these alternatives has resulted  in  a  reduction  in  the  size  of  the  grouper-tilefish  fleet.  In  the most recent annual review of the program (GMFMC  2015), researchers found that the number of shareholders  had fallen from 766 original shareholders to 628 in 2014.  In this sense, the IFQ program has been successful from  Fishermen  now  lease  gag  grouper  for  $2.50  a  pound.  Fishermen catch them and get paid $5.00 a pound. Govern- ment gets their 3 percent catch cut, that’s another $.15, so  they’ve got $2.65 right off the top, they’re getting $2.45  net for their black groupers. They were getting paid more  than that thirty years ago, for crying out loud. Their fuel  costs and all their expenses have to be paid, their captain,  crew, bait, everything has to be paid out of their $2.45  cents they’re netting after they lease their quota. It’s turned  the fishermen into sharecroppers. an economic perspective, however much it disrupted social  relations of production within the fishery. Has the program,  however,  achieved  its  second  goal,  increasing  economic  efficiency in the fishery?

Prior  to  the  IFQ  program,  grouper-tilefish  fishermen  tended to fish the fishery hard during the early part of the  year,  engaging  in  derby  fishing  and  fishing  out  the  quota  within a few weeks or months, regardless of weather condi- tions or vessel maintenance needs. This contributed to high  safety risks and resulted in flooding the market with grouper  and  tilefish,  which  depressed  the  price.  Most  fishermen  interviewed complained that, prior to the IFQ, fish dealers  held all of the power at the market; they could, in short, name  their price by claiming that they already had a high volume  of grouper and tilefish.

With the IFQ, fishermen can “choose their weather” as  well as schedule their fishing activity over the course of the  year. Most fishermen interviewed said that this had, indeed,  shifted the balance of power at the market, in that now they  can land fish through the year and prevent an over-supply  depressing  prices.  This  claim  is  somewhat  borne  out  by  ex-vessel  price  data.  Figure  1  shows  the  price  per  pound  for red grouper, the species with the highest landings, from  2005 to 2015. It shows that between 2005 and 2009, the five  years prior to the implementation of the IFQ program, prices  remained more or less steady at around $2.30 to $2.50 per  pound; beginning in 2010, however, the price begins rising  steadily,  from  $2.57  in  2010  to  $3.34  in  2015.5  It  can  be  argued, then, that the IFQ program has not only given more  power to the fishermen over their catch, it has also allowed  for increased planning through the year, reduced or elimi- nated derby fishing, and stabilized work in the fishery so that  captains and crew can be employed through the year rather  than just during the first weeks. All of these outcomes would  suggest that the program has improved economic efficiency.  This may have occurred at the expense of those who could  not demonstrate, for whatever reasons, historical participation  in fishery, but it has seemed to have achieved the two goals  that economic science predicted it would achieve. It should  be noted, however, that increased safety (i.e., an end to derby  fishing)  has  not  always  accompanied  the  implementation  of an IFQ. Emery, et al. (2014) found that fishing fatalities  increased after an IFQ was implemented in the Tasmanian  rock lobster fishery, specifically because fishermen having to  lease quota would fish in foul weather and take other risks if  they believed they would receive higher prices at the market,  thus making up more of their lease expense.

We need to keep in mind, however, that ultimately the  Magnuson-Stevens Act’s principal charge has been to pro- tect fish stocks first, and fishermen or fishing communities  second.  This  is  more  or  less  the  same  charge  that  derives  from people who espouse the theory of the tragedy of the  commons:  that  privatizing  natural  resources  will  result  in  Improving Economic Efficiency Figure 2.  Red Grouper Prices before and after IFQ program, 2005-2015 protecting those resources because individuals will have a  vested interest in the reproduction of the resource. As Wolf  (1982) points out, however, natural resources, such as furs,  that  are  often  seen  as  diminishing  resources—destined  to  eventual extinction—tend to be accessed via methods other  than privatization. Have IFQ shareholders come to view the  fisheries resources of the Gulf as their own? Or do they view  them as diminishing resources, subject to eventual depletion  beyond what is economically viable? Has the IFQ program,  in other words, also been a success in terms of its biological  goals of preventing overfishing? Or, like sacrificing access to  the many for the private use of the few, might accomplishing  economic goals have deleterious ecological consequences?  Although the Magnuson-Stevens Act includes National  Standard  8,  which  says  that  regulators  must  consider  the  impacts of new regulations on fishing communities, the Act  also states that priority be given to rebuilding fish stocks that  are either overfished or subject to overfishing. As such, the  principal goal of the IFQ has been to reduce fishing pressure  on fish in the grouper-tilefish complex. While the IFQ may  accomplish this for fish in the complex, many fishermen we  interviewed reported other resource-related problems have  emerged from IFQ implementation.

Resource-minded commercial fishermen in the Gulf of  Mexico, in line with fishermen all up and down the South  Atlantic coast (Griffith 2011), will typically argue that the  most biologically sound method of fishing is to “fish over  the entire resource.” In other words, rather than specializing  in one or a handful of similar species, such as the species in  the grouper-tilefish complex, it is more ecologically sound to  shift among a number of species throughout the year and even  from year to year, allowing those species that have been fished  heavily to recover. Valdes-Pizzini and Garcia-Quijano (2009)  documented this strategy in Puerto Rico as well. This strategy  may be sound from an economic efficiency perspective as  overfished species are more difficult and time-consuming to  find, forcing fishermen to burn more fuel to catch the same  amount of fish.

Instead of encouraging fishing over a range of species,  the  grouper-tilefish  IFQ  program  rewarded  those  who  had  specialized in the fishery: quite simply, those who had built  up a history of high annual grouper-tilefish landings received  more shares than those who had smaller landings histories.  By extension, it also signaled to fishermen that if they want  to receive shares in future IFQ programs, they need to build  up similar landings histories. In the words of one interviewed  fisherman, “You don’t get rewarded for this [fishing for many  species]. They rewarded the ones who worked them to death.”  Criticism of the IFQ program wasn’t restricted to spe- cialization. Another relationship that came up again and again  was  how  the  IFQ  program  was  liable  to  influence  fishing  pressures  on  other  species.  Fishermen  expressed  this  in  a  few ways. First, some fishermen who received shares in the  grouper-tilefish  fishery  began  leasing  some  or  all  of  their  shares  and  then  either  began  fishing  for  or  devoted  more  effort  to  fishing  for  other  species,  principally  vermillion  snapper, king mackerel, and amberjack.6 Others, now able  to  pick  and  choose  what  times of  the  year  they  could  fish  for grouper, had begun moving among a variety of species  through the year, depending on their availability. In the words  of one fisherman: “In the winter, when the smaller fish aren’t  biting, I’ll go to my grouper, and then in the summer months  I’ll go to beeliners (vermillion snapper) and porgies (white  grunt) and stuff like that.” It’s interesting that he referred to  the grouper with the possessive pronoun, now considering  them “his” to fish whenever he wasn’t fishing for something  else. This is, of course, in line with the strategy of fishing  over the entire resource, which some critics of the program  argued it discouraged.

A third criticism of the program, that it promotes what  are known as “regulatory discards,” is in line with a moral  economic argument. Regulatory discards are individual fish  that are caught incidentally while fishing for other species  but that, due to regulations, either cannot be landed or are  not landed because they do not conform to the preferences of  seafood dealers. They tend to be discarded and, rather than  contributing to the reproduction of the resource, simply die  and become part of the marine food web. I have interviewed  fishermen across the United States Southeast and Puerto Rico  for nearly three decades, and regulatory discards have always  emerged as a moral issue, with fishermen nearly always op- posed to discarding perfectly good fish because regulations or  the market will not let them land them. Yet, they do discard  fish due to regulatory or market considerations. One of my most memorable fieldwork experiences was  spending  the  evening  with  a  fisherman  in  the Albemarle  Sound, who, due to regulations, could keep only five striped  bass (known locally as rock or rock fish) as by-catch from  his gill nets every fishing trip. Because fishing was his liveli- hood, he kept the five which would bring the highest price at  the market, having to discard those he had caught and kept  previously each time he caught a superior fish. This practice  is known as “high grading” and has become common in the  aftermath of the Gulf IFQ programs. And in the words of the  Albemarle Sound fishermen, all the regulations were about  were, “Killing rock, killing rock, killing rock” (Griffith 1999).  In his critical review of ITQs, Copes (1986:285) notes that  some fishermen, “to obtain the greatest net value from the  quota…may  well  be  induced  to  ‘high-grade’  his  catch  by  discarding fish of lesser quality.”

High grading has also occurred in the aftermath of the  IFQ  program.  Those  with  few  pounds  in  the  complex,  in  particular, have an incentive to keep only those fish that will  bring the highest prices at the market. Fishermen interviewed  said that this tended to be a four- to five-pound fish, which  dealers preferred because this was the size that restaurants,  which paid the highest prices, preferred. Evidently, they can  filet fish this size into individual portions without waste.  In  addition  to  IFQ-spawned  changes  in  fishing  effort  and  regulatory  discards,  fishermen  believed  that  the  IFQ  program in red snapper had contributed to an increase in the  snapper population—a development that, in conjunction with  the  effects  of  Gulf  hurricanes  and  the  Deepwater  Horizon  oil spill, shifted the territory of red snapper so that more of  them were congregating in the eastern part of the Gulf. This  altered the dynamics of the food web in that red snapper, as  voracious feeders, became nuisance fish to grouper-tilefish  fishermen. “Now that you put snapper on a quota,” one fisher- man complained, “they are an aggressive fish. He’ll eat that  small grouper, and he’ll eat the hell out of that small beeliner  (Vermillion  snapper). Anytime  you  boost  one  population,  you push another population down.” Several other fishermen  made similar statements, with some saying that they had to  fish through red snapper to get to the grouper stocks. One  fisherman said that since the increase in the snapper popula- tion, he now had to spend time “teaching” the snapper that  he was fishing so that they would learn to let the hooks drop  to the grouper.

While biological data to support fishermen’s claims has  not yet become available, both fishermen and fish biologists  who have presented work to the Gulf Council agreed that the  red snapper population has rebounded to a point that it has  become almost a nuisance fish. They also agreed that the fish  has enlarged its territory, now colonizing areas in the eastern  Gulf of Mexico that were formerly primarily grouper habitat.  Grouper fishermen in these regions did not have the chance  to establish history in the red snapper program because snap- per were simply not there when the landings that qualified  fishermen were being calculated.  Given the mixed outcomes of the IFQ program, is it any  wonder that the 21st century has begun badly for the science  of  economics? Achieving  the  IFQ’s  economic  goals  has  clearly had negative human consequences (what economists  might  refer  to  as  “costs,”),  facilitating  a  kind  of  incipient  class formation. The implementation of an IFQ program in  the Gulf of Mexico grouper-tilefish fishery clearly rewarded  those with capital (vessel owners and permit holders) while  disenfranchising those who provide the bulk of the labor to  the fishery: captains without their own vessels and crew. As  is common under capitalism, that class formation resulted in  greater concentration of wealth and greater accumulation of  value among IFQ shareholders from the wealth shares of those  who fish for them. In this sense, IFQs are in line with national  and global trends toward proletarianization, which, in recent  years, have resulted in widening income gaps between the rich  and the poor. At the same time, by rewarding specialization,  the program encouraged fishing styles that may well result  in  placing  vermillion  snapper  and  other  species  at  risk  of  overfishing. Increasing efficiency and reducing overcapac- ity may be fueling the very biological conditions that move  fishery managers to create IFQ programs in the first place.

This has had an interesting, if perhaps perverse, impact  on the cultural history of Gulf of Mexico fisheries. Amazingly,  the program has managed to turn history into a commodity.  Specifically, one’s history of participation in the fishery, once  converted to shares, embodies a history that can be bought  and sold on the open market, transferring from the seller of a  permit and vessel with its associated catch history to a buyer.  In fact, I encountered a case where a fisherman purchased  another fisherman’s  catch history with the purchase of his  vessel and permit just prior to the allocation of shares; the  buyer received the other fisherman’s history and thus received  a significant share in the fishery while the seller, having sold  his history, left commercial fishing.  Enforcing  the  principles  of  IFQ  programs  illustrates  the  more  general  problems  associated  with  the  privileging  of  economic science. To achieve narrow goals such as efficiency,  economists tend to ignore the ways that economic behaviors  are  embedded  in  wider  fields  of  power,  social  relationships,  cultural values, and moral economic sentiments. Indeed, some  economists advocate ignoring the embeddedness of economic  and social behavior, considering it just so much external noise  that distracts from the elegance of mathematical modeling, a  position that Granovetter (1985) critiques. Selective economic  analysis has had consequences as deep and divisive as the mul- tiple economic crises listed in this article’s opening paragraph.  Are these scholarly practices so different from the current politi- cized assaults on climate change science or evolution? Shouldn’t  economists  themselves,  after  Doeringer  and  his  colleagues  (1986), be among the first to acknowledge when their methods  and  assumptions  are  not  only  flawed  but  disruptive?  Indeed,  shouldn’t all social scientists be the first to understand that value,  embedded in family and community, is a deeply human thing?
